Introduction¶

Many of watch love to watch movies. We spend a considerable amount of time of our lives watching movies. These movies are often of different genres, budgets, directed by industry's biggest and amateur directors alike, with stellar performances by the world's greatest actors.

Over the past couple of years, movie making has grown rapidly with more and more movies being produced and consumed every year.

As Data Analysts, we not only watch movies but at the same time, can't help but wonder what goes into making these movies, how does the movie making industry work and how has it evolved through the years.

What are the top production companies and which companies rolled out the most movies?

What are some of the best and worst movies of the world so far and on what parameters?

Which movies are the most popular among viewers, which movies made the most profit and gave the most ROI figures?

Who are the most successful directors and movie stars?

Does runtime of movie matter? In today's world of hyperactivity and instant gratification behavior, the attention span of people is going down with passing time, are the changes being reflected in movies too? Is there an optimal runtime or should movie-makers just 'go for it'?

And finally what are the metrics on what revenue making capabilities of movie matter?

As part of the Investigate a dataset exercise, I am trying to find the answer to most of these questions by analysing a TMDb movies database which contains collection of about 10k+ movies, with important details including the budget, revenue, release dates among other information.

Assumptions:

  1. It is assumed that the currency of the relevant fields are in US currency, dollars for the purpose of study.
  2. It is also assumed that some fields are redundant and do not contribute to the overall study results.
  3. For directors and Cast Members, only the first field values are considered for the top Director and Actor category.

Research Questions:

  1. How is the film making industry evolving?

    • How much more movies people are consuming now compared to last few decades? (Growth Rate)
    • Is movie making a profitable business?
    • What are the some of the best and the not-so-good performing movies across different parameters through the years?

  1. Does runtime hold any importance? What is the preferred runtime of viewers?

    • How has the average runtime of movies changed over the years?
    • What is the Average Runtime of movies currently?
    • Is there any visible relationship between Revenue and Popularity with Runtime?
  1. What are The top 10 movies of the world based on different parameters?

  1. Genres

    • What are the main movie genres and distribution of movies across genres?
    • How do different Genres perform across different parameters?

  1. Who are the most successful movie directors and film stars?

    • Does having the most popular director or actor ensure financial success in the box office?
  1. Does having the most popular director or actor ensure financial success in the box office?

  1. Which are the biggest production companies that dominate the industry?

    • Number of movies churned by those production companies
    • Budget spending, revenue generation and ROI of those companies
  1. How does Revenue depend on different parameters?

Data Wrangling and Cleaning

  1. Based on variables are the most appropriate and significant for answering our questions, a few columns have been removed which would not serve useful for our research purposes such as 'imdb_id', budget_adj', 'revenue_adj', 'homepage', 'keywords', 'overview'
  1. There were a few records specifically in Budget or Revenue fields with entry as '0'. Calculating profits based on these values would lead to unwanted results. So, those rows were deleted from the Data frame.
  1. This dataset also has duplicate rows. These were removed for our purposes.
  1. The 'Release Date' column was not in the correct Date format. These were appropriately converted.

#Replacing the 0 values with Numpy Data type NaN

df['revenue'].replace(0, np.NaN, inplace = True)
df['runtime'].replace(0, np.NaN, inplace = True)
In [12]:
#Now dropping these NA values because any other technique(replacing with mean, last value etc.) doesn't make sense
df.dropna(axis=0, inplace=True)
In [13]:
#Splitting the Cast, Director and Genres columns to extract the data
df_cast = (df['cast'].str.split('|', expand=True).rename(columns=lambda x: f"cast_{x+1}"))
df_dir = (df['director'].str.split('|', expand=True).rename(columns=lambda x: f"director_{x+1}"))
df_gen = (df['genres'].str.split('|', expand=True).rename(columns=lambda x: f"genres_{x+1}"))
df_prod = (df['production_companies'].str.split('|', expand=True).rename(columns=lambda x: f"production_companies_{x+1}"))

#When using expand=True, the split elements will expand out into separate columns.
In [14]:
#Removing the old columns and joining back the new columns
df = df.drop(['cast', 'director', 'genres', 'production_companies'], axis = 1)
df = df.join([df_cast, df_dir, df_gen, df_prod])
In [15]:
#Changing Release date type to Standard Datetime format
df.release_date = pd.to_datetime(df['release_date'])

#And the float64 types to int64 types for ease of plotting
col = ['popularity', 'budget', 'revenue', 'vote_average']
df[col] = df[col].astype(np.int64)
In [16]:
#Renaming Budget, Revenue columns based on assumption of currency and adding Profit, ROI columns 
df.insert(3, 'profit_US_dollars', (df['revenue'] - df['budget']))
df.insert(4, 'ROI', (df['profit_US_dollars']/df['budget']))
df.rename(columns = {'budget':'budget_US_dollars', 'revenue':'revenue_US_dollars'}, inplace = True)

def maxmin(val):
    
    min1 = df[val].idxmin()
    max1 = df[val].idxmax()
    
    max2 = pd.DataFrame(df.loc[max1,:])
    max2.columns = [df['original_title'][max1]]
    min2 = pd.DataFrame(df.loc[min1,:])
    min2.columns = [df['original_title'][min1]]
    
    print(color.BOLD + color.RED)
    print(''.join(['Movie with Highest ' + val + ' --> ', df['original_title'][max1]]), end=' --> ')
    print(df[val][max1])
    print(''.join(['Movie with Lowest ' + val + ' --> ', df['original_title'][min1]]), end=' --> ')
    print(df[val][min1])

def top10(val):
    
    info = (df[val].sort_values(ascending=False)).head(10)
    
    arr = []
    for i in info.index.values:
        arr.append((df['original_title'][i], info[i]))
    
    arr = pd.DataFrame(arr)
        
    choose = {'popularity':'red', 'budget_US_dollars':'green', 'revenue_US_dollars':'blue', \
            'profit_US_dollars':'magenta', 'runtime':'purple', 'vote_count':'orange', 'ROI':'violet'}
    title = {'popularity':"Popularity", 'budget_US_dollars':'Budget', 'revenue_US_dollars':'Revenue', \
            'profit_US_dollars':'Profit', 'runtime':'Runtime', 'vote_count':'Votes', 'ROI':'ROI'}
    
    ax = sns.barplot(x=arr[1], y=arr[0], data=arr, color = choose[val])
    
    sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(14, 5)})
    ax.set_title('Movies with Highest ' + title[val], fontsize = 15)
    ax.set_xlabel(title[val], fontsize = 18)
    ax.set_ylabel("Movies", fontsize = 18)
    ax.grid(False)
    sns.set_style("whitegrid")
    plt.show()

def direct(val):
    
    test5 = df.sort_values(by=val, ascending=False)

    sns.barplot(test5[val].iloc[:20], test5.director_1.iloc[:20], palette='autumn', errwidth=0)

    params = {'figure.figsize': (14, 5), 'axes.labelsize':15, 'axes.titlesize':20}

    plt.rcParams.update(params)

    plt.title("Director with the highest " + val, fontsize=20)
    plt.xlabel(val, fontsize=25)
    plt.yticks(fontsize=15)
    plt.ylabel('Director', fontsize=25)
    plt.xticks(fontsize=15)
    plt.grid(False)
    
    #plt.tight_layout()
    
    plt.show()

def dir_year(val1, val2, val3):
    
    a = df[df.release_year.between(val2, val3, inclusive=True)].sort_values(by=val1, ascending=False)[val1][:20]
    b = df[df.release_year.between(val2, val3, inclusive=True)].sort_values(by=val1, ascending=False)['director_1'][:20]
    
    sns.barplot(a, b, palette='rocket', errwidth=False)
    
    params = {'figure.figsize': (18, 6), 'axes.labelsize':15, 'axes.titlesize':20}

    plt.rcParams.update(params)
    
    plt.title('Top 20 Directors of every decade starting from '+str(val2)+' to '+str(val3) + 
              ' based on ' + val1 + '\n', 
              fontsize=30)
    
    plt.xlabel(val1.upper(), fontsize=25)
    plt.ylabel('Directors', fontsize=25)
    plt.yticks(fontsize=15)

Research Questions:

  1. How is the film making industry evolving?

    - How much more movies people are consuming now compared to last few decades? (Growth Rate)

    These are the growth rates compared on a 20-year basis.

    It is evident that number of movies produced has sky-rocketed rapidly through the years based on the following growth rate figures:

    From 1960 -> 1980: It has increased about 340% From 1980 -> 2000: It increased 378% From 2000 -> 2015: It increased 92%

    - Is movie making a profitable business?

    We can see from the graph that from 2000 onwards, the budget that goes into making movies was almost constant whereas the Revenue and Profit rose significantly thus proving that movie making is a highly profitable industry. A steady investment seems to yield growing revenues and profits.

    - What are the some of the best and the not-so-good performing movies across different parameters through the years?

    The list of the best and the worst movies reveal a few interesting trivia. For e.g. the movie with the highest budget ($40 Million) is also the movies with the lowest Profits, which is almost equal to the budget itself!

    Talk about tanking at the box office.

    There’s a movie with runtime of 338mins while there’s also a movie with runtime of 15mins! These are easily very distinct outliers. Jurassic World is the most popular movie while the Karate Kid part2 is the movie which has given the highest ROI.

  2. Does runtime hold any importance? What is the preferred runtime of viewers?

    - How has the average runtime of movies changed over the years?

    Studies suggest that in a short span of 15 years, an average human’s attention span has reduced from 12secs to around 8secs! We now have an attention span which is less than that of a goldfish! Go figure.

    This has an implication for movie makers as audience would now demand more narrow, focused, targeted and crisp content.

    Which as seen from the trend curve of Movie runtimes through the years, it’s evident that movies are also reflecting the change. The runtime has gone down from the highest count of around 170mins in 1965 to around 110mins in the period between 2000 to 2015.

    - What is the Average Runtime of movies currently?

    From the boxplots, it is evident that that the average runtime of movie varies between ~96min to ~120max with outliers at ~250mins, ~350mins and ~15mins. From the violin plot, we can see that most movies have a runtime between 90 to 110mins as distribution of movies around that range is maximum.

    - Is there any visible relationship between Revenue and Popularity with Runtime?

    From the two Histograms of Revenue vs Runtime and Popularity vs Runtime, it is clear that movies between runtime of 140-150mins brings the most moolah and movies between 140-145mins are the most popular.

    So runtime seems to have a significant impact on Revenue and Popularity.

    However, there’s a contradiction where movies between 115-125mins seem to be very popular among viewers but they are bringing very less revenue to producers.

    If we look at the Avg. Runtime comparison of Movie Genres, we can see that the genres - War, History and Western fits the description of genres between 115-125 mins. Also, if we look at the popularity distribution of these genres, we can see that they are relatively quite popular.

    Now if we compare the revenue brought in by these 3 genres, we can see all 3 genres score very low in Revenue. So, we might conclude that although Western, War and History movies are popular among viewers, they don’t bring as much revenue as they should.

  1. What are The top 10 movies of the world based on different parameters?

    The plot of top 10 movies futher explores the movies based on different parameters.

    Based on popularity index, most movies are recent releases with Jurassic World leading the table.

    The movie with the highest budget i.e. The Warrior’s way is followed by mostly newer movies. Since overall, the budget figures are lesser for 2000-2015, it can be assumed that the movies in the list must have had a significant budget over their counter-parts to top the list.

    The movie which made the highest profits are Avatar, Star wars and Titanic with 2 of those movies being directed by James Cameron.

    The movie with the highest runtime can easily be considered epics with Carlos and Cleopatra having runtimes of 350 and 250mins approx respectively!

    The movie with highest ROI is The karate Kid part2 which far surpasses its counterparts in that category.

  1. Genres

    - What are the main movie genres and distribution of movies across genres?

    Genres-Popularity over the years

    1960-1980: From 1960-1980, the film genres that were most popular were Adventure, Animation and Mystery. Surprisingly, there was a huge popularity of Foreign Movies during this period.

    1980-2000: This period saw the emergence of War and Western movies among the popular Genres. Animation continued to lead with Science fiction also emerging as the new favourite.

    2000-2015: During this period, almost all genres saw a boom in popularity with Adventure, Fantasy and Science Fiction sky-rocketing! Foreign films unfortunately didn’t rise in popularity after 1980s.

    Hence, we can see that non-popular genres like Fantasy, Science Fiction and Animation movies have evolved through the years and have actually become popular among audiences. However, genres like Foreign Films took a backtrack and eventually disappeared from the popular list.

    - How do different Genres perform across different parameters?

    Genres(Runtime)

    Looking at the distribution of runtime for various genres, we can see that Western, War and history movies have the highest runtimes among all the genres, followed by Drama, Action and adventure. Animation and T.V. movies are among the lowest spectrum of runtimes.

    Genres(Popularity)

    Looking at the popularity scores of Genres, Adventure, Fantasy and Science Fiction seems to be the most popular genres followed by Animation, Family and Action.

    Genres(Budget, Revenue and Profit)

    As seen from a previous plot, Budget of movies has been in a steady while revenue and profit figures are higher for a given budget invested.

    The Genres which get the most investment are Action, Adventure, Animation followed by Family and Fantasy. And why wouldn’t producers be unhappy with it, the revenue and profits seem almost proportional to the budget invested in almost all Genres except Foreign genre movies which seem to have a negative profit! Sigh! The audience doesn’t seem to appreciate Foreign movies much.

  1. Who are the most successful movie directors and film stars?

    Some of the top directors in terms of Revenue and profit generation abilities are also very popular and have high vote counts with a few exceptions.

    Movies which have very high ratings have directors with high ratings too.

    If we compare decade wise, we can see some interesting figures. For e.g. in 1970-1979, George Lucas with his glorious Star Wars franchise far exceeds any other directors in terms of popularity. Similarly, during 2000-2009, James Cameron with movies like Terminator and Avatar is the most popular director of that decade.

    Among the modern directors, Colin Trevorrow and George Miller are the most popular directors.

    Among the casts, Sam Worthington brings in the most revenue and is most profitable although on a popularity basis, he doesn’t rate very high on the list.

    Popularity doesn’t always mean a high revenue and profitability and vice-versa, a trend which was seen in the case of the top directors too.

  1. Does having the most popular director or actor ensure financial success in the box office?

    It can be seen that having the most popular director doesn’t always ensure financial success of the movie nor a director who brings in the most revenue have to be necessarily the most popular. This fact is very visibly highlighted in the graphs for e.g. from 2000-2015, the top 3 popular actors were Chris Pratt, Tom Hardy and Matthew McConaughey while Sam Worthington, Harrison Ford and Robert Downey Jr. Brought in the most revenue. Maybe their association with top profitable franchises may be responsible for this.

  1. Which are the biggest production companies that dominate the industry?

    The top production companies of the world are Universal pictures, Paramount pictures and Columbia pictures with 280, 270 and 180 movies produced respectively!

    These production companies do not feature on the top 3 production houses with most budget though with Universal and Paramount on the far end of the spectrum suggesting that these houses might be rolling out a lot of low budget movies, quantity over quality perhaps.

    Or perhaps, Walt Disney, Marvel and DC with their superhero movies may be needing to put more money on the bag to produce their genre of movies.

    The 2 production houses which dominate the revenue figures are surprisingly not in the top budget list suggesting that these might be rolling out more quality movies than others. DC comics unfortunately do not earn as much as they put into their budget.

    Columbia pictures Corp. Have the highest ROI figures far exceeding rivals suggesting that they excel in churning out the maximum profit with the minimum investment.

  1. How does Revenue depend on different parameters?

    Finally looking at the scatterplot of Revenue vs other important parameters, it is evident that Revenue strongly depends on Budget of the movies, their popularity, their Vote count and Runtime, a fact that was almost always evident almost throughout the entire study. The more the money spent on budget, promotions, film making, the more the revenue and profits. High revenue movies are always on the top popular list and vice-versa whereas there seems to be an optimal region of Runtime of movies where Revenue seems to be the maximum concentrated.
